\"><path d=\"M9 8h-3v4h3v12h5v-12h3.642l.358-4h-4v-1.667c0-.955.192-1.333 1.115-1.333h2.885v-5h-3.808c-3.596 0-5.192 1.583-5.192 4.615v3.385z\"/></svg>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"social-icon social-icon-linkedin\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"https://www.linkedin.com/shareArticle?mini=true&#038;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nasa.gov%2Fdirectorates%2Farmd%2Ftacp%2Fui%2Fabout-ui%2F\" aria-label=\"Share on LinkedIn.\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path d=\"M4.98 3.5c0 1.381-1.11 2.5-2.48 2.5s-2.48-1.119-2.48-2.5c0-1.38 1.11-2.5 2.48-2.5s2.48 1.12 2.48 2.5zm.02 4.5h-5v16h5v-16zm7.982 0h-4.968v16h4.969v-8.399c0-4.67 6.029-5.052 6.029 0v8.399h4.988v-10.131c0-7.88-8.922-7.593-11.018-3.714v-2.155z\"/></svg>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<li class=\"social-icon social-icon-rss\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<a href=\"/feed/\" aria-label=\"Subscribe to RSS feed.\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" viewBox=\"0 0 800 800\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><path d=\"M493 652H392c0-134-111-244-244-244V307c189 0 345 156 345 345zm71 0c0-228-188-416-416-416V132c285 0 520 235 520 520z\"/><circle cx=\"219\" cy=\"581\" r=\"71\"/></svg>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t</a>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t</li>\n\t\t\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\t\t<div class=\"grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-5 padding-right-4 margin-bottom-5 desktop:margin-bottom-0\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"padding-top-3 border-top-1px border-color-carbon-black\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"margin-bottom-2\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<h2 class=\"heading-14\">Details</h2>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"grid-row margin-bottom-3\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"grid-col-4\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"subheading\">Last Updated</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"grid-col-8\">Mar 11, 2026</div>\n\t\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"grid-row margin-bottom-3\"><div class=\"grid-col-4\"><div class=\"subheading\">Editor</div></div><div class=\"grid-col-8\">Lillian Gipson</div></div><div class=\"grid-row margin-bottom-3\"><div class=\"grid-col-4\"><div class=\"subheading\">Contact</div></div><div class=\"grid-col-8\"><div class=\"margin-bottom-3\"><div>Jim Banke</div><div><a href=\"mailto:j&#105;&#109;&#46;&#98;&#97;&#110;k&#101;&#64;n&#97;&#115;&#97;&#46;go&#118;\">ji&#109;.&#98;an&#107;e&#64;na&#115;&#97;.&#103;ov</a></div></div></div></div>\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div>\n\t<div class=\"grid-col-12 desktop:grid-col-5 padding-right-4 margin-bottom-5 desktop:margin-bottom-0\"><div class=\"padding-top-3 border-top-1px border-color-carbon-black \"><div class=\"margin-bottom-2\"><h2 class=\"heading-14\">Related Terms</h2></div><ul class=\"article-tags\"><li class=\"article-tag\"><a href=\"https://www.nasa.gov/nasa-directorates/armd/tacp/ui/\">University Innovation</a></li></ul></div></div>\n\t</div>\n</section>\n\t</div>]]></content:encoded>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\t\t</item>\n\t\t<item>\n\t\t<title>Telescopes Team Up for New View of Cat&#8217;s Eye Nebula</title>\n\t\t<link>https://www.nasa.gov/image-article/telescopes-team-up-for-new-view-of-cats-eye-nebula/</link>\n\t\t\n\t\t<dc:creator><![CDATA[Monika Luabeya]]></dc:creator>\n\t\t<pubDate>Wed, 11 Mar 2026 15:53:43 +0000</pubDate>\n\t\t\t\t<category><![CDATA[Hubble Space Telescope]]></category>\n\t\t<category><![CDATA[Planetary Nebulae]]></category>\n\t\t<guid isPermaLink=\"false\">https://www.nasa.gov/?post_type=image-article&#038;p=971703</guid>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t<description><![CDATA[This March 3, 2026, image combines views from ESA&#8217;s (European Space Agency) Euclid and NASA&#8217;s Hubble Space Telescope to feature one of the most visually intricate remnants of a dying star: the Cat’s Eye Nebula, also known as NGC 6543. This extraordinary planetary nebula lies 4,400 light-years away in the constellation Draco and has captivated astronomers for decades [&#8230;]]]></description>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id=\"\" class=\"hds-media hds-module wp-block-image\"><div class=\"margin-left-auto margin-right-auto nasa-block-align-inline\"><div class=\"hds-media-wrapper margin-left-auto margin-right-auto\"><figure class=\"hds-media-inner hds-cover-wrapper hds-media-ratio-cover \"><a href=\"https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg\"><img decoding=\"async\" width=\"2048\" height=\"1123\" src=\"https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?w=2048\" class=\"attachment-2048x2048 size-2048x2048\" alt=\"A planetary nebula in space. The star in the very center is surrounded by white bubbles and loops of gas, all shining with a powerful blue light. Farther away a broken ring of red and blue gas clouds surrounds the nebula. A multitude of golden and white stars, wisps of gas and distant galaxies of various sizes surround the nebula on the black background.\" style=\"transform: scale(1); transform-origin: 50% 50%; object-position: 50% 50%; object-fit: cover;\" block_context=\"nasa-block\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg 2048w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=300,165 300w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=768,421 768w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=1024,562 1024w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=1536,842 1536w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=400,219 400w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=600,329 600w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=900,494 900w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=1200,658 1200w, https://www.nasa.gov/wp-content/uploads/2026/03/hubble-euclid-catseye-2026-pubtiff-4k-potm2602c.jpg?resize=2000,1097 2000w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 2048px) 100vw, 2048px\" /></a></figure><figcaption class=\"hds-caption padding-y-2\"><div class=\"hds-credits\">ESA/Hubble &amp; NASA, ESA Euclid/Euclid Consortium/NASA/Q1-2025, J.-C. Cuillandre &amp; E. Bertin (CEA Paris-Saclay), Z. Tsvetanov</div></figcaption></div></div></div>\n\n\n<p>This March 3, 2026, image combines views from <a href=\"https://www.esa.int/Science_Exploration/Space_Science/Euclid\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\">ESA&#8217;s (European Space Agency) Euclid</a> and NASA&#8217;s Hubble Space Telescope to feature one of the most visually intricate remnants of a dying star: the Cat’s Eye Nebula, also known as NGC 6543. This extraordinary <a href=\"https://science.nasa.gov/mission/hubble/multimedia/hubble-glossary/#h-planetary-nebula\" rel=\"noopener\">planetary nebula</a> lies 4,400 light-years away in the constellation Draco and has captivated astronomers for decades with its elaborate and multilayered structure.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"https://science.nasa.gov/missions/hubble/two-observatories-one-cosmic-eye-hubble-and-euclid-view-cats-eye-nebula/\" rel=\"noopener\">See what this observation reveals about this planetary nebula.</a></p>\n\n\n\n<p><em>Image credit: ESA/Hubble &amp; NASA, ESA Euclid/Euclid Consortium/NASA/Q1-2025, J.-C. Cuillandre &amp; E. Bertin (CEA Paris-Saclay), Z. Tsvetanov</em></p>\n]]></content:encoded>\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\t\t</item>\n\t\t<item>\n\t\t<title>Curiosity Blog, Sols 4825-4831: Exploring the Borderlands</title>\n\t\t<link>https://science.nasa.gov/blog/curiosity-blog-sols-4825-4831-exploring-the-borderlands/</link>\n\t\t\n\t\t<dc:creator><![CDATA[]]></dc:creator>\n\t\t<pubDate>Wed, 11 Mar 2026 05:24:17 +0000</pubDate>\n\t\t\t\t<category><![CDATA[Blogs]]></category>\n\t\t<guid isPermaLink=\"false\">https://science.nasa.gov/blog/curiosity-blog-sols-4825-4831-exploring-the-borderlands/</guid>\n\n\t\t\t\t\t<description><![CDATA[Written by William Farrand, Senior Research Scientist, Space Science Institute Earth planning date: Friday, March 6, 2026 Curiosity is in the last stage of its exploration of the spiderweb-like boxwork unit. This stage consists of exploring the eastern and southern borders of this terrain. There were two multi-sol plans assembled this week. The previous plan […]]]></description>\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id=\"\" class=\" hds-module hds-module-full alignfull wp-block-nasa-blocks-secondary-navigation\">\n<div class=\"hds-secondary-navigation-wrapper z-top width-100 padding-0\">\n<div id=\"\" class=\"hds-secondary-navigation width-full border-bottom-1px text-center hds-color-mode-dark hds-module hds-module-full alignfull wp-block-nasa-blocks-hdsnav\"><button type=\"button\" class=\"hds-secondary-nav-mobile-button display-flex tablet:display-flex desktop:display-none width-full flex-align-center bg-carbon-90 border-color-carbon-80 color-spacesuit-white\" aria-expanded=\"false\" aria-controls=\"hds-secondary-nav-track\"><span>Curiosity Navigation</span><svg width=\"16\" height=\"16\" alt=\"\" enable-background=\"new 0 0 400 400\" viewBox=\"0 0 400 400\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\"><path d=\"m4.2 122.2 195.1 195.1 196.5-196.6-37.9-38-157.8 157.8-156.8-156.8z\" /></svg></button></p>\n<div class=\"hds-secondary-nav-track grid-container grid-container-extrawide padding-0 tablet:padding-x-3 desktop:padding-x-2 \">\n<div class=\"hds-secondary-navigation-menu-items\">\n<nav>\n<ul class=\"usa-nav__primary usa-accordion flex-justify-center margin-0\">\n<li class=\"usa-nav__primary-item\"><button type=\"button\" class=\"usa-accordion__button usa-nav__link\" aria-expanded=\"false\"